## Implementation Details

The webhook handler has two layers:

1. **Route handler** (`apps/dashboard/src/app/api/webhooks/github/route.ts`) -- HTTP layer: parse body, verify signature, deduplicate, dispatch to core handler, return 200 quickly.
2. **Core handler** (`packages/core/src/github/webhooks.ts`) -- Business logic: look up project, create deployment, enqueue build.

### Layer 1: Route Handler Updates

#### File: `apps/dashboard/src/app/api/webhooks/github/route.ts`

After the existing signature verification, add:

```typescript
// 1. Parse the JSON payload
const payload: WebhookPayload = JSON.parse(body);

// 2. Deduplicate by delivery ID
const db = getDb();
const isDuplicate = await checkDeliveryId(db, deliveryId);
if (isDuplicate) {
  return NextResponse.json({ received: true, deduplicated: true });
}
await recordDeliveryId(db, deliveryId);

// 3. Dispatch to core webhook handler (fire-and-forget for async work)
// The handler creates the deployment record synchronously, then enqueues the build.
try {
  await handleWebhook({
    db,
    payload,
    event,
    deliveryId,
  });
} catch (err) {
  // Log the error but still return 200 to GitHub.
  // GitHub will retry on non-2xx, which would cause duplicate processing.
  logger.error({ err, event, deliveryId }, "Webhook handler error");
}

return NextResponse.json({ received: true });
```

**Deduplication strategy:** Use a simple in-memory Set for delivery IDs (suitable for single-instance deployment). If the platform scales to multiple instances, replace with a database table.

```typescript
// Simple in-memory deduplication (single-instance safe)
const processedDeliveries = new Set<string>();
const MAX_DELIVERY_CACHE = 10000;

function checkDeliveryId(_db: Database, deliveryId: string): boolean {
  return processedDeliveries.has(deliveryId);
}

function recordDeliveryId(_db: Database, deliveryId: string): void {
  processedDeliveries.add(deliveryId);
  // Prevent unbounded memory growth
  if (processedDeliveries.size > MAX_DELIVERY_CACHE) {
    const oldest = processedDeliveries.values().next().value;
    if (oldest) processedDeliveries.delete(oldest);
  }
}
```

**Alternative (database-backed):** If database deduplication is preferred, create a `webhook_deliveries` table with `delivery_id TEXT PRIMARY KEY` and `processed_at TIMESTAMPTZ`. Check existence before processing, insert after. This approach survives server restarts but adds a DB query to every webhook.

### Layer 2: Core Handler Updates

#### File: `packages/core/src/github/webhooks.ts`

Implement the three event handlers:

##### Push Event Handler

```typescript
case "push":
  await handlePushEvent(ctx);
  break;
```

```typescript
async function handlePushEvent(ctx: WebhookContext): Promise<void> {
  const { db, payload } = ctx;

  // 1. Extract branch from ref (e.g., "refs/heads/main" -> "main")
  if (!payload.ref || !payload.after || !payload.repository || !payload.installation) {
    logger.warn("Push event missing required fields, skipping");
    return;
  }

  const branch = payload.ref.replace("refs/heads/", "");
  const commitSha = payload.after;
  const repoFullName = payload.repository.full_name;
  const installationId = payload.installation.id;

  // 2. Look up the project by installation ID and repo name
  const [project] = await db
    .select()
    .from(projects)
    .where(
      and(
        eq(projects.githubInstallationId, installationId),
        eq(projects.githubRepoFullName, repoFullName),
      ),
    );

  if (!project) {
    logger.info({ repoFullName, installationId }, "No project found for push event");
    return;
  }

  // 3. Check if the push is to the production branch
  if (branch !== project.productionBranch) {
    logger.debug(
      { branch, productionBranch: project.productionBranch },
      "Push to non-production branch, skipping",
    );
    return;
  }

  // 4. Create deployment record
  const [deployment] = await db
    .insert(deployments)
    .values({
      projectId: project.id,
      type: "production",
      status: "queued",
      commitSha,
      branch,
    })
    .returning();

  logger.info(
    { deploymentId: deployment.id, projectId: project.id, commitSha },
    "Production deployment created from push event",
  );

  // 5. Enqueue build (async -- the queue processes builds sequentially)
  const queue = getBuildQueue();
  await queue.enqueue({
    id: deployment.id,
    projectId: project.id,
    execute: async () => {
      // Full build+deploy pipeline will be called here.
      // Updates deployment status through: queued -> building -> deploying -> ready/failed
    },
  });
}
```

