##### Installation Event Handler

```typescript
case "installation":
  await handleInstallationEvent(ctx);
  break;
```

```typescript
async function handleInstallationEvent(ctx: WebhookContext): Promise<void> {
  const { db, payload } = ctx;
  const action = payload.action;

  if (!payload.installation) {
    logger.warn("Installation event missing installation data");
    return;
  }

  const { id, account } = payload.installation;

  if (action === "created") {
    // Upsert the installation record
    await db
      .insert(githubInstallations)
      .values({
        id,
        githubAccountLogin: account.login,
        githubAccountType: account.type,
      })
      .onConflictDoNothing();

    logger.info({ installationId: id, account: account.login }, "GitHub App installed");
  } else if (action === "deleted") {
    // Remove the installation record
    await db
      .delete(githubInstallations)
      .where(eq(githubInstallations.id, id));

    logger.info({ installationId: id }, "GitHub App uninstalled");
  }
}
```

---

## Webhook Flow Diagram

```
GitHub sends POST /api/webhooks/github
    |
    v
1. Read body as text, extract headers (signature, event, deliveryId)
    |
    v
2. Verify HMAC-SHA256 signature  -------> 401 if invalid
    |
    v
3. Check delivery ID deduplication -----> 200 { deduplicated: true } if seen before
    |
    v
4. Parse JSON payload
    |
    v
5. Dispatch by event type:
    |
    +-- "push" ---------> handlePushEvent()
    |                         |
    |                         +-- Extract branch from ref
    |                         +-- Look up project by installationId + repoFullName
    |                         +-- Skip if non-production branch
    |                         +-- Create deployment record (status: "queued")
    |                         +-- Enqueue build via BuildQueue
    |
    +-- "pull_request" -> handlePullRequestEvent()
    |                         |
    |                         +-- Log event (placeholder for Phase 7)
    |
    +-- "installation" -> handleInstallationEvent()
    |                         |
    |                         +-- "created": upsert into github_installations
    |                         +-- "deleted": delete from github_installations
    |
    +-- (other) ---------> Log and ignore
    |
    v
6. Return 200 { received: true }
```

---

## Response Time Requirement

The webhook handler MUST return a 200 response within 500ms. GitHub's webhook delivery timeout is 10 seconds, but responding quickly prevents queue buildup on GitHub's side.

All slow operations (build, deploy, container management) run asynchronously via the `BuildQueue`. The synchronous path is:
1. Signature verification (~1ms)
2. Deduplication check (~1ms for in-memory, ~5ms for DB)
3. JSON parsing (~1ms)
4. Project lookup (~5ms database query)
5. Deployment record insert (~5ms database query)
6. Queue enqueue (~1ms, in-memory)

Total synchronous time: ~15ms.

